{"TopicId":212899,"ForumId":119,"TopicTitle":"Different Celestial Body Properties are Presented In the Tracking Station, Why?","CreatedByName":"ShadoxFilms","CreatedById":197189,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-02-26T03:01:11Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"ShadoxFilms","CreatedById":197189,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-02-26T03:01:11Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNow that KSP2 is out for early access, I\u0027ve been looking through the tracking station for any changes to the properties of celestial bodies to update some of my Python scripts to help plan missions.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOne of the things that is new, is that circumference is given, instead of radius. While the value of the body radius can be calculated simply from circumfrence, which is needed for many orbital calculations (at least for perfect spheres), I do wonder why the change.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI guess the main question that stands is, what drove the changes in the displayed data in the tracking station, and for non-spherical bodies (dres has a nasty protrusion at the equator, but for future bodies that may be more oblate than not) how do the devs plan to communicate the details to the player (average radius, equitorial radius, etc). Side note: I am absolutely in love with the added precision for the values that are given!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nPictures are of KSP1 vs. KSP2 Kerbin Parameters\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cbr\u003E\n\u003Cimg alt=\u00229NKEjVs.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u002288.43\u0022 height=\u0022405\u0022 width=\u0022458\u0022 src=\u0022https://i.imgur.com/9NKEjVs.png\u0022\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022IrnzbWG.png\u0022 class=\u0022ipsImage\u0022 data-ratio=\u0022151.67\u0022 height=\u0022709\u0022 style=\u0022width:300px;height:auto;\u0022 width=\u0022467\u0022 src=\u0022https://i.imgur.com/IrnzbWG.png\u0022\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMaybe I\u0027m just being too OCD about this, I\u0027d love to know other players thoughts, especially those who love the mission planning side of things.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nBest,\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAlso, the term \u0022Atmosphere\u0022 In KSP2 is slightly confusing\u003Cbr\u003E\nIn aerospace, atm is a unit of pressure (1atm = 101,325 Pa), however given the value of 1.225, I think they are referring to density.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nUnless kerbin in KSP2 does have a 1.225 atm. at Sea Level, which corresponds to a pressure of 124.12 KPa\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222023-02-26T03:03:43Z\u0022 title=\u002202/26/2023 03:03  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00221 yr\u0022\u003EFebruary 26, 2023\u003C/time\u003E by ShadoxFilms\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"J.Random","CreatedById":63332,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-02-26T03:58:36Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSidenote: do devs measure time in m/s? No wonder fizzicks is so weird.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Chilkoot","CreatedById":175911,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-02-26T04:05:04Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI noticed earlier today that Kerbin\u0027s gravity is 1.00034 m/s^2, rather than 1.00034 g.\u00A0 I can only assume that\u0027s a typo?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"ShadoxFilms","CreatedById":197189,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-02-26T04:11:08Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224243309\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022212899\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221677384304\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022175911\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Chilkoot\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n8 minutes ago, Chilkoot said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI noticed earlier today that Kerbin\u0027s gravity is 1.00034 m/s^2, rather than 1.00034 g.\u00A0 I can only assume that\u0027s a typo?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nGood Catch! You can see the comparison in my pictures, I think you\u0027re right. Honestly I didn\u0027t even notice.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224243296\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022212899\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221677383916\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002263332\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022J.Random\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n14 minutes ago, J.Random said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSidenote: do devs measure time in m/s? No wonder fizzicks is so weird.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYeah, units seem to be whack in the new tracking station\u003Cbr\u003E\n(sidereal period is a measurement of how much time it takes to complete 360 degrees rotation in a fixed reference frame, in units of seconds, but tracking station reports units of m/s)\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222023-02-26T04:13:15Z\u0022 title=\u002202/26/2023 04:13  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00221 yr\u0022\u003EFebruary 26, 2023\u003C/time\u003E by ShadoxFilms\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Nazalassa","CreatedById":217956,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-02-26T10:52:14Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nAlso I don\u0027t think Kerbin has a circumference of 1,130,973,386,764.53 m, else its radius would be 180,000,002,144.17 m which is (I\u0027ll ditch the floating-point errors) around 180 \u003Cem\u003Ebillion\u003C/em\u003E kilometers.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"The Aziz","CreatedById":150811,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-02-26T10:55:39Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nJool and Kerbol are marked as terrestrial planets.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"GoldForest","CreatedById":77770,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-02-26T11:01:30Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224243828\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022212899\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221677408939\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022150811\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022The Aziz\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n5 minutes ago, The Aziz said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nJool and Kerbol are marked as terrestrial planets.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHonestly, a very Kerbol thing to do. Every kerbal dreams of one day walking on the Sun.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Nazalassa","CreatedById":217956,"CreatedDateTime":"2023-02-26T11:03:34Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00224243828\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022212899\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221677408939\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022150811\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022The Aziz\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n7 minutes ago, The Aziz said:\n\u003C/div\u003E